06827nam a22014295i 9780691186085DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20202019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2019954861  a97806911860857 a10.1515/97806911860852doi  a(DE-B1597)539904  a(OCoLC)1135668643  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aMED0620002bisacsh1 aAktipis, Athena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cheating Cell :bHow Evolution Helps Us Understand and Treat Cancer /cAthena Aktipis. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b19 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Evolution in the Flesh -- t2. Why Does Cancer Evolve? -- t3. Cheating in Multicellular Cooperation -- t4. Cancer from Womb to Tomb -- t5. Cancer across the Tree of Life -- t6. The Hidden World of Cancer Cells -- t7. How to Control Cancer -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA fundamental and groundbreaking reassessment of how we view and manage cancer When we think of the forces driving cancer, we don't necessarily think of evolution. But evolution and cancer are closely linked, for the historical processes that created life also created cancer. The Cheating Cell delves into this extraordinary relationship, and shows that by understanding cancer's evolutionary origins, researchers can come up with more effective, revolutionary treatments. Athena Aktipis goes back billions of years to explore when unicellular forms became multicellular organisms. Within these bodies of cooperating cells, cheating ones arose, overusing resources and replicating out of control, giving rise to cancer. Aktipis illustrates how evolution has paved the way for cancer's ubiquity, and why it will exist as long as multicellular life does. Even so, she argues, this doesn't mean we should give up on treating cancer-in fact evolutionary approaches offer new and promising options for the disease's prevention and treatments that aim at long-term management rather than simple eradication. Looking across species-from sponges and cacti to dogs and elephants-we are discovering new mechanisms of tumor suppression and the many ways that multicellular life-forms have evolved to keep cancer under control. By accepting that cancer is a part of our biological past, present, and future-and that we cannot win a war against evolution-treatments can become smarter, more strategic, and more humane. Unifying the latest research from biology, ecology, medicine, and social science, The Cheating Cell challenges us to rethink cancer's fundamental nature and our relationship to it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aMEDICAL / Oncology.2bisacsh  aAdaptive Oncogenesis.  aAzra Raza.  aCancer the Evolutionary Legacy.  aEmperor of All Maladies.  aJames DeGregori.  aKat Arney.  aMel Greaves.  aRichard Dawkins.  aSelfish Monsters.  aSiddhartha Mukherjee.  aTazmanian devil.  aThe First Cell.  aThe Selfish Gene.  aadaptive therapy.  abattle.  abeat.  abenign.  abreast cancer.  acactus cancer.  acancer transmission.  acellular.  acheater.  aclinical trial.  aconflict.  acontainment.  acooperation theory.  adoctor.  aecosystem.  afight.  afree rider.  agenomic.  ageriatric.  aimmunity.  aimmunology.  aimmunotherapy.  alung cancer.  amalignant.  amaternal.  amedical.  amedicine.  ametastasis.  ametastasize.  amicrobial mediators.  amulticellularity.  anatural selection.  aoncologist.  aoncology.  apaternal.  aphysician.  aprostate cancer.  apublic h